# argus DB-backup signature VERIFY key — Ed25519 public key (PEM). NON-SECRET, committed on purpose:
# pinning it in git makes it tamper-evident and means restore reads the verify key from the repo, never from
# the same bucket an attacker could write. The matching PRIVATE key lives ONLY in Key Vault
# (argus-backup-signing-key) and on the backup host's tmpfs at sign time — never here.
#
# PLACEHOLDER — the real key does not exist until the operator generates it. Signature verification at restore
# (slice 3) FAILS CLOSED against this placeholder, which is correct: an unpopulated verify key must not pass.
# (Slice 3 must reject this by CONTENT — grep REPLACE_WITH_ and hard-abort with a legible message — not rely
# only on `openssl pkey -pubin` failing to parse, so the operator sees "verify key not populated", not a
# generic parse error.)
# To populate (one-time, after running populate-keyvault.sh which creates argus-backup-signing-key):
#   az keyvault secret show --vault-name <vault> --name argus-backup-signing-key --query value -o tsv \
#     | openssl pkey -pubout
# Replace the block below with that "-----BEGIN PUBLIC KEY-----" output and commit.
# See infra/backup/README.md §"Backup signing key" and docs/threat-models/db-backup.md.
-----BEGIN PUBLIC KEY-----
REPLACE_WITH_ARGUS_BACKUP_VERIFY_PUBLIC_KEY
-----END PUBLIC KEY-----
